ences -- tTWELVE National Honor and Practical Kinship: Unwanted Women and Children -- tTHIRTEEN Political Demography: The Banning of Abortion in Ceausescu's Romania -- tFOURTEEN From Reproduction to HIV: Blurring Categories, Shifting Positions -- tFIFTEEN Physical and Cultural Reproduction in a Post-Chernobyl Norwegian Sami Community -- tPART FIVE What's So New about the New Reproductive Technologies? -- tSIXTEEN Public Servants, Professionals, and Feminists: The Politics of Contraceptive Research in Brazil -- tSEVENTEEN The Normalization of Prenatal Diagnostic Screening -- tEIGHTEEN Postmodern Procreation: A Cultural Account of Assisted Reproduction -- tNINETEEN Displacing Knowledge: Technology and the Consequences for Kinship -- tPART SIX What's Political about Reproduction? -- tTWENTY Interrogating the Concept of Reproduction in the Eighteenth Century -- tTWENTY-ONE The Body as Property: A Feminist Re-vision -- tTWENTY-TWO Reassessing Reproduction in Social Theory -- tTWENTY-THREE Misreading Darwin on Reproduction: Reductionism in Evolutionary Theory -- tNOTES ON CONTRIBUTORS0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis groundbreaking volume provides a dramatic investigation of the dynamics of reproduction. In an unusually broad spectrum of essays, a distinguished group of international feminist scholars and activists explores the complexity of contemporary sexual politics around the globe. Using reproduction as an entry point in the study of social life and placing it at the center of social theory, the authors examine how cultures are produced, contested, and transformed as people imagine their collective future in the creation of the next generation.The studies encompass a wide variety of subjects, from the impact of AIDS on reproduction in the United States to the aftereffects of Chernobyl on the Sami people in Norway and the impact of totalitarian abortion and birth control policies in Romania and China. The contributors use historical and comparative perspectives to illuminate the multiple and intersecting forms of power and resistance through which reproduction is given cultural weight and social form. They discuss the ways that seemingly distant influences shape and constrain local reproductive experiences such as the international flows of adoptive babies and childcare workers and the Victorian and imperial legacy of eugenics and family planning.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aGender Studies. 4aSocial Science. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh1 aAnagnost, Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarroso, Carmen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrowner, Carole H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColen, Shellee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorrêa, Sônia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDas, Veena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEraser, Gertrude J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFranklin, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGinsburg, Faye D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGinsburg, Faye D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJordanova, Ludmilla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaufert, Patricia Leyland, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKligman, Gail, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLewin, Ellen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin, Emily, econtributor.